    "prompt": "<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of a horizontal disk with a block on the surface of the disk. A line extends upward from the center of the disk and a circular arrow around the line points counter-clockwise. At the bottom of the line, another arrow points to the right and is labeled&nbsp; R and ends at the center of the bottom of the block.\" height=\"132\" src=\"/images/b24f0d5ad6741339c15f4b238b20a80b.png\" width=\"225\"></div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a graph. The horizontal axis is labeled R, in meters, and the numbers 0, 0.1, 0.2, and 0.3 are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled v squared sub max, in open parenthesis, meters per second, close parenthesis squared, and the numbers 0 through 1.6, in increments of 0.2, are indicated. There are 16 points of data. The coordinate of the data are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. 0.02 meter, 0.2 meter per second squared; 0.042 meter, 0.39 meter per second squared; 0.057 meter, 0.37 meter per second squared; 0.061 meter, 0.50 meter per second squared; 0.081 meter, 0.59 meter per second squared; 0.099 meter, 0.57 meter per second squared; 0.119 meter, 0.65 meter per second squared; 0.139 meter, 0.79 meter per second squared; 0.159 meter, 0.89 meter per second squared; 0.163 meter, 0.99 meter per second squared; 0.18 meter, 1.0 meter per second squared; 0.202 meter, 1.18 meters per second squared; 0.21 meter, 1.09 meters per second squared; 0.233 meter, 1.22 meters per second squared; 0.242 meter, 1.39 meters per second squared; 0.265 meter, 1.37 meters per second squared.\" height=\"204\" src=\"/images/d01651c8fcd0cfe0949d5b9fc74ce564.png\" width=\"365\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">During an experiment, a block of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M equals 0.20 kilogram\"><math alttext=\"M equals 0.20 kilogram\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.20</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>kg</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is placed on a disk that rotates about an axle through its center, as shown in the diagram. The block is moved to different distances <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the axle, and the tangential speed of the block is gradually increased until the mass begins to slip. The distance and maximum tangential speed before slipping, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub max\"><math alttext=\"v sub max\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>max</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></math></span></span>, are recorded. A student creates a graph of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v sub max squared\"><math alttext=\"v sub max squared\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msup><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>max</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> as a function of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, as shown. How should the student use the graph to most accurately determine the experimental value of the coefficient of static friction <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"mu sub s\"><math alttext=\"mu sub s\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> between the block and the disk?</p>\n",
